===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `ed` command is a classic line-oriented text editor in Unix/Linux. It is used to edit files through the terminal.  Working with `ed` can be more challenging compared to modern editors like `nano` or `vim`, but it's useful for scripting and simple tasks.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `ed filename`  --> 📝 Open a file for editing.
    🔹 `.`             --> 📍 In `ed`, the dot (.) represents the current line.
    🔹 `,p`            --> 📃 Print all lines.
    🔹 `w`             --> 💾 Save changes to the file.
    🔹 `q`             --> 👋 Quit `ed`.  It will prompt if changes haven't been saved.
    🔹 `1,$s/old/new/g` --> 🔄 Replace all occurrences of "old" with "new" on all lines.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ ed myfile.txt

    🔹 Opens the file `myfile.txt` with `ed`.

    ,p

    🔹 Prints the entire content of the file.

    w

    🔹 Saves the changes.

    q

    🔹 Exits the editor.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ ed newfile.txt
    a
    Hello World!
    .
    ,p
    Hello World!
    w
    14
    q

    🔹 Creates and edits a new file with `ed`. The `a` (append) command is used to add text to the file. The dot (.) indicates the end of the input. `w` saves the file, and `q` quits `ed`. `14` is the number of characters written to the file.

